Perspectives on Sino-American Relations 2019
NEW YORK – In 2018, the new and increasingly unpredictable dynamics of Sino-American relations had wide parts of Asia worried.
A year ago, US President Donald Trump returned from his particularly pompous "State Visit Plus" in Beijing, which China hoped would mark the end of Trump's anti-Chinese campaign rhetoric.
Twelve months later, China and the United States are entangled in a trade war, and the US government has replaced America's "strategic engagement" with China with "strategic competition."
In addition, the US, European, and Chinese economies and markets were booming a year ago.
Today there is great uncertainty on financial markets, with growth slowing in China and Europe and higher interest rates starting to take effect in the United States.
The uncertainty about the future development of the nuclear negotiations with North Korea also clouds the picture.
What, then, are the prospects for relations between the USA and China in 2019?
It is likely that an agreement on reducing the bilateral trade deficit and on the import decisions that China will make will be reached by March.
An agreement on tariff cuts is also possible by then, although the complexity of the issue could extend the envisaged time frame.
Würde ein Zoll nach dem anderen verhandelt, könnte ein Jahr ins Land gehen.
Sollten chinesische Wirtschaftsreformer aber einen drastischeren Ansatz wählen, indem sie sich im Laufe der Zeit zur Abschaffung aller Zölle bekennen und die Amerikaner auffordern, es ihnen gleichzutun, könnte ein schnelleres Resultat vorliegen.
Das würde allerdings chinesischen Handelsbeamten zuwiderlaufen, die seit Jahrzehnten geschult werden wenig herzuschenken, geschweige denn alles auf einmal.
Die Reform des sogenannten erzwungenen Technologietransfers sollte relativ unkompliziert sein.
Nichtsdestotrotz ist eine Reform etwas anderes als die Art und Weise, wie vertragliche Vereinbarungen in der Praxis ausgelegt werden könnten, auch wenn es gar keine spezifischen Bestimmungen zum Technologietransfer geben sollte.
The protection of intellectual property is, however, extremely problematic.
Prior agreements made under President Barack Obama's administration could potentially be reaffirmed.
However, enforcing them or pursuing judicial actions for violations of intellectual property rights remains a hopeless endeavor.
A possible mechanism would be to submit relevant agreements between Chinese and foreign companies to trade arbitration institutions in Singapore or Switzerland, which are specifically tasked with enforcing intellectual property rights protection.
If China objects, it could develop its own international arbitration procedure that is based in China.
For this, it would have to include qualified foreigners in its dispute resolution body to strengthen its international credibility.
No one has confidence in Chinese trade courts.
To meet its own domestic reform needs, China must move towards completely independent trade and civil chambers within its judicial system, even though the criminal chamber remains subject to political control.
The concerns of the United States regarding state subsidies under the country's "Made in China 2025" strategy will hardly be alleviated.
Fact is that all countries provide some level of state support to their domestic technology sectors, although this is highest in China.
Even if we were to prescribe a maximum level of state support for a particular company, adherence would be difficult to assess.
I am not optimistic that there will be a negotiation outcome in this area.
Maybe America just has to knock China out of the running by increasing public investments in research and development in the fields of information technology and biotechnology.
We should also not rule out the possibility that China offers customs reforms to the rest of the international community.
Over time, China might decide to take such a drastic step as to agree to free trade not only with the USA but with all member states of the World Trade Organization.
Auf diese Weise böte sich China eine nahezu unwiderstehliche Gelegenheit sich als Verfechter des globalen Freihandels zu positionieren und dem Trend zum Protektionismus Einhalt zu gebieten.
Im Zuge einer solchen Wende könnte China die Mitgliedstaaten des transpazifischen Freihandelsabkommens TPP um einen Beitritt ersuchen, um die USA (die als eine der ersten Amtshandlungen Trumps aus dem Freihandelsabkommen ausgestiegen sind) in der Region Asien-Pazifik zu überflügeln.
China kann bemerkenswert leichtfüßig sein, wenn es eine politische Bresche und Marktöffnung entdeckt.
Die Verhandlungen wären schwierig, aber die Vorbehalte Japans gegenüber dem Beitritt Chinas zum TPP haben sich seit dem jüngsten Besuch von Ministerpräsident Shinzo Abe in Peking verringert.
Angesichts der zentralen strategischen Herausforderungen im Verhältnis zu den USA, dürfte China 2019 in der allgemeinen Außen- und Sicherheitspolitik bestrebt sein, Konflikte in seinen Beziehungen zu anderen Ländern abzubauen.
In the relations with Japan, there is already a certain normalization.
The latest data from the Japanese Coast Guard point to a significant decrease in Chinese incursions into the waters around the Senkaku/Diaoyu Islands in the East China Sea.
China also seeks to ease tensions with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations over the South China Sea through the accelerated negotiation of a "Code of Conduct".
Furthermore, China might have a more relaxed relationship with India following the bilateral summit in Wuhan in April.
Additionally, China could start moderating its stance towards Taiwan, given the electoral setback suffered by the Democratic Progressive Party of Taiwanese President Tsai Ing-wen, which advocates independence, in local and regional elections last month.
This would naturally change radically if the USA continues with further significant arms sales to Taiwan, which is likely.
There are still incidents at sea involving the USA in the South China Sea, and the conflict could intensify if the USA more vigorously underscores their stance on "freedom of navigation" next year.
Across Eurasia, China will continue to implement its grand project "Belt and Road."
However, the initiative has caused less political turmoil in China over the past few months.
There are already discussions among Chinese officials about revising certain modalities, following Sri Lanka's handover of the Hambantota port to China, which sparked negative reactions and raised concerns about the long-term financial sustainability of the New Silk Road.
2019 could therefore less frequently hear triumphant reports about the New Silk Road.
In addition, China is likely to strengthen and expand its role within the United Nations and existing Bretton Woods institutions rather than highlighting new institutions for international political action.
It will probably continue to appear as a new advocate for the WHO and maintain its stance on the global climate change issue, as agreed in the Paris Climate Agreement of 2015.
More sober-minded representatives of the foreign policy establishment in China believe it is better to focus on the existing mechanisms of the global rule-based system, especially if the United States consistently shows contempt for them.
While China tries to stabilize its relations with the United States and reduce tensions in its relations with other countries, its leadership will probably use 2019 to form a well-founded judgment on the future of US policy: the consequences of the Mueller investigation for Trump and his administration, and whether a new president in 2020 (or earlier) would alter the new US strategy in any way.
Although they have already come to the conclusion that America's attitude towards China has fundamentally changed, they are still unsure about the exact form this change takes and whether a fundamental strategic shift (as opposed to tactical measures) is called for.
